28 antiquos ac veteres· · · potuerunt etc. : The entire statement is somewhat strained in expression, but quite in conformity with Aper’s style. The speaker's main object was to show that Cicero and his contemporaries were not entitled to the name ‘antiqui‚' because they are not removed from the orators of the present time by more than an ordinary lifetime. In accordance with this view, he regards the possibility that both Cicero and the modern orators might have been heard by the same audiences, as the chronological connecting-link between them.
